'''Granit Xhaka''' ({{IPA|sq|gɾanit d͡ʒaka|lang}}, born 27 September 1992) is a Swiss professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[defensive midfielder]] for and [[Captain (association football)|captains]] both {{English football updater|Sunderld}} club [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] and the [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland national team]].

Xhaka began his career with [[FC Basel|Basel]] and won the [[Swiss Super League]] twice. He moved to [[Borussia Mönchengladbach]] in 2012, developing a reputation as a technically gifted player and natural leader alongside criticism for his temperament, and acted as [[Captain (association football)|club captain]] from 2015, twice leading the team to [[UEFA Champions League]] qualification.

Xhaka signed for Premier League club [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in 2016 for a fee in the region of £30 million, making nearly 300 appearances over seven years, serving as captain, and winning two [[FA Cup]]s. In 2023, he returned to the [[Bundesliga]] with [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]], helping the club to their [[2023–24 Bundesliga|first-ever league title]] in his debut season.

Xhaka was part of the [[Switzerland national under-17 football team|Swiss team]] that won the [[2009 FIFA U-17 World Cup]]. He made his senior debut in 2011 and is currently the nation's [[Switzerland national football team#Most appearances|record appearance holder]], with 145 caps. He represented [[Switzerland]] at the [[FIFA World Cup]] in [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014]], [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]] and [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]], and the [[UEFA European Championship]] in [[UEFA Euro 2016|2016]], [[UEFA Euro 2020|2020]] and [[UEFA Euro 2024|2024]].

==Early life==
The younger brother of Basel player [[Taulant Xhaka]], Granit Xhaka<ref>{{cite web |date=15 November 2022 |title=FIFA World Cup Qatar 2022™: List of Players: Switzerland |url=https://fdp.fifa.org/assetspublic/ce44/pdf/SquadLists-English.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221218195301/https://fdp.fifa.org/assetspublic/ce44/pdf/SquadLists-English.pdf |archive-date=18 December 2022 |publisher=FIFA |page=30}}</ref> was born on 27 September 1992<ref>{{Cite web |title=Granit Xhaka - Sunderland Midfielder - ESPN (UK) |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/player/_/id/149981/granit-xhaka |access-date=2026-02-12 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref> in the city of [[Basel]], Switzerland, into an ethnic Albanian family from [[Podujevë|Besianë]], Kosovo.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hytner |first=David |date=2017-11-17 |title=Granit Xhaka: 'My dad's first few months in jail were OK, then the beatings started' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/nov/17/granit-xhaka-dad-jail-beatings-arsenal-tottenham-derby |access-date=2026-02-12 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Hytner |first=David |date=2017-05-26 |title=Arsenal's Granit Xhaka fired by his father's struggle for freedom |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/may/26/granit-xhaka-arsenal-fa-cup |access-date=2026-02-12 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The family moved from Besianë to Basel in 1990.<ref>{{Cite web |last= |title=FC Basel - Die offizielle Website |url=http://www.fcb.ch/sport/show/playerDetailByID/-/30167/72/9/36/de-de/-/25328 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701182423/http://www.fcb.ch/sport/show/playerDetailByID/-/30167/72/9/36/de-de/-/25328 |archive-date=2014-07-01 |access-date=2026-02-12 |website=www.fcb.ch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.panorama.com.al/2011/11/16/xhaka-zgjodha-pa-hezitim-zvicren-shqiptaret-me-thone-tradhtar/ |title=Xhaka: Zgjodha pa hezitim Zvicrën, shqiptarët më thonë tradhtar! |quote=Granit, familja juaj vjen nga Serbia, po ju ku keni lindur? Në Zvicër, në Bazel kam lindur. Ashtu si Taulanti, vëllai im. Disa burime informacioni, duke përfshirë këtu edhe "Ëikipedia", kanë njoftuar se kam lindur në Kosovë, por kjo nuk është e vërtetë |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140514225243/http://www.panorama.com.al/2011/11/16/xhaka-zgjodha-pa-hezitim-zvicren-shqiptaret-me-thone-tradhtar/ |archive-date=14 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.20min.ch/sport/fussball/story/14450158 |title=Albanien hat schon telefoniert |date=11 November 2009 |quote=Bei Granits Mutter beisst der albanische Fussballverband denn auch auf Granit: «Unsere Kinder sind hier geboren worden und zur Schule gegangen. Sie gehören in die Schweiz.»}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Granit Xhaka: 5 things on the Bayer Leverkusen midfielder signed from Arsenal |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/granit-xhaka-5-things-on-the-bayer-leverkusen-midfielder-arsenal-gladbach-23764 |access-date=2023-08-06 |website=bundesliga.com – the official Bundesliga website |language=en}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Basel===
[[File:Granit Xhaka.jpg|thumb|upright|Xhaka warming up for [[FC Basel|Basel]] in 2011]] 
Xhaka started his youth football with [[FC Concordia Basel|Concordia Basel]] and, together with his brother [[Taulant Xhaka|Taulant]], moved to the youth department of [[FC Basel|Basel]] at the end of 2002. He played for various Basel youth teams regularly advancing through the ranks. In the 2006–07 season he was member of the U-15 team that won the Swiss championship, creating a record for eternity. They managed to win all championship games in that season to win the Swiss championship at that level. This was achieved with a goal difference of 104:13. Since competitive football began in Switzerland, no team had achieved this before.<ref name="fcb-aktuell-2007-06-17-U-16-Meister">{{cite web | year = 2006 | url = http://www.fcb.ch/news/show/byItemID/de-de/-/18566/27/7/7 | title = U15 mit Rekord für die Ewigkeit | trans-title = U15 with a record for eternity | publisher = FC Basel 1893 | accessdate = 2007-06-17 | language = de-ch | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140106040711/http://www.fcb.ch/news/show/byItemID/de-de/-/18566/27/7/7 | archive-date = 6 January 2014 | url-status = dead }}</ref> In the 2007–08 season he was member of the U-16 team that won the Swiss championship at that level, remaining undefeated throughout the entire season.<ref name="fcb-aktuell-2008-06-15-U-18-Cupsieger">{{cite web |last=FC Basel 1893 |year=2008 |title=Zwei weitere Nachwuchstitel für den FCB |trans-title=Two more youth titles for FCB |url=http://www.fcb.ch/news/show/byItemID/de-de/-/20378/27/7/7 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106040536/http://www.fcb.ch/news/show/byItemID/de-de/-/20378/27/7/7 |archive-date=6 January 2014 |accessdate=2008-06-15 |publisher=FC Basel 1893 |language=de-ch}}</ref> During the 2008–09 season Xhaka advanced to the U-18 team, but was nevertheless called up to Basel's U-21 team, who played in the third tier of Swiss football, by their coach [[Patrick Rahmen]] and on 15 November 2008 Xhaka was substituted on in the 83rd minute as Basel won 2–1 against [[SC Cham|Cham]]. During the second half of the season Xhaka played nine further games for the U-21, scoring one goal and at the end of the season became division champions and won the championship at U-21 level.<ref name="rsssf-Switzerland 2008/09">{{cite web |last=Stokkermans |first=Karel |author-link= |year=2012 |title=Switzerland 2008/09 |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tablesz/zwit2009.html |access-date=2023-11-16 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |language=fr}}{{Dead link|date=June 2024|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> To the beginning of the 2009–10 season Xhaka advanced to become member of the U-21 squad, however was still eligible to play for the U-18 team, who at the end of the season became Swiss champions at their level.

To the beginning of their [[2010–11 FC Basel season|2010–11 season]], Xhaka advanced to Basel's first team under head coach [[Thorsten Fink]]. On 28 July 2010, Xhaka played his first team debut in the third qualifying round of the [[2010–11 UEFA Champions League]] in the away match against [[Debreceni VSC|Debrecen]]. He was substituted on in the 88th minute and four minutes later he scored the team's second goal to secure the victory.<ref name="Uefa-UCL-2010/11-Debrecen-FCB">{{cite web | first = Matthew | last = Watson-Broughton  | author-link = | date = 28 July 2010 | url = https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/01e7-0ea18e54cc1a-895a1a8578fc-1000--basel-do-enough-to-down-debrecen/ | title = Basel do enough to down Debrecen | format = | publisher = [[UEFA]] | access-date = 2023-11-16}}</ref> He played his [[Swiss Super League|domestic league]] debut for the club. playing the full 90 minutes, in the away game on 21 August as Basel played a 1–1 draw with [[FC Thun|Thun]].<ref name="fcb-achiv-2010/11-Thun-FCB">{{cite web | last = Verein "Basler Fussballarchiv” | author-link = | date = 21 August 2010 | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=17647 | title = FC Thun – FC Basel 1:1 (0:0) | format = | publisher = Verein "Basler Fussballarchiv" | access-date = 2023-11-16}}</ref> He scored his first Super League goal for his new team on 15 May 2011, in the home game in the [[St. Jakob-Park]] as Basel won 5–1 against [[FC Thun|Thun]].<ref name="fcb-aktuell-2010/11-FCB-Thun">{{cite web |last=Meister |first=Remo |date=15 May 2011 |title=Der FCB ist zurück an der Spitze |trans-title=FCB is back at the top |url=http://www.fcb.ch/news/show/byItemID/-/10044/25972/26/7/7 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405060814/http://www.fcb.ch/news/show/byItemID/-/10044/25972/26/7/7 |archive-date=5 April 2012 |access-date=15 May 2011 |publisher=FC Basel 1893 |language=de}}</ref> At the end of the [[2010–11 Swiss Super League|2010–11 league season]], Xhaka won the championship title with the team. He had 20 league appearances, scoring once.<ref name="rsssf-Switzerland 2010/2011">{{cite web | first = Anthony | last = Zea | author-link = | year =2012 | url = http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwit11.html | title = Switzerland 2010/2011 | publisher = Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation | access-date = 2023-11-16}}</ref>

At the end of the 2011–12 season Xhaka won the [[Double (association football)|Double]] with the team. They won the [[2011–12 Swiss Super League|League]] Championship title with 20 points advantage over second placed [[FC Luzern|Luzern]].<ref name="fcb-aktuel-2011/12-Meistertitel">{{cite web |last=Meister |first=Remo |date=29 April 2012 |title=Der 15. Meistertitel für den FCB – die Bilanz einer grandiosen Saison |trans-title=The 15th championship title for FCB – the summary of a magnificent season |url=http://www.fcb.ch/news/show/byItemID/de-de/10044/27863/26/7/7 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016142727/http://www.fcb.ch/news/show/byItemID/de-de/10044/27863/26/7/7 |archive-date=16 October 2013 |access-date=29 April 2012 |publisher=FC Basel 1893 |language=de}}</ref> The final of the [[2011–12 Swiss Cup]] was played in the [[Stade de Suisse, Wankdorf|Stade de Suisse]] on 16 May 2012. The game ended with a one-all draw after extra time and winning the penalty shoot-out Basel lifted the trophy.<ref name="rsssf-Switzerland 2011/12">{{cite web | first = Karel | last = Stokkermans | author-link = | year = 2017 | url = https://www.rsssf.org/tablesz/zwit2012.html | title = Switzerland 2011/12 | publisher = Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation | language = fr | access-date = 2023-11-16}}</ref> At the end of the season he left the club, during his time with Basel's first team Xhaka played a total of 67 competitive games for them scoring a three goals. 44 of these games were in the [[Swiss Super League]], nine in the [[Swiss Cup]], 14 in the UEFA competitions (Champions League and Europa League). He scored two goals in the domestic league and one in the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]].<ref name="fcb-achiv-Granit Xhaka">{{cite web | last = Verein "Basler Fussballarchiv” | authorlink = | year = 2023 | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/spieler?command=detail&id=6587 | title = Granit Xhaka | format = | publisher = Verein "Basler Fussballarchiv” | accessdate = 2023-11-16}}</ref>

===Borussia Mönchengladbach===
[[File:Xhaka 1.jpg|thumb|upright|Xhaka playing for [[Borussia Mönchengladbach]] in 2015]]

On 18 May 2012, Basel announced on their homepage that Xhaka had agreed terms with [[Lucien Favre]]'s [[Borussia Mönchengladbach]]. After medical checks were completed, Xhaka signed a five-year deal with the club. The transfer fee was not disclosed by Mönchengladbach, but is estimated to be in the region of €8.5&nbsp;million.<ref name="fcb4">{{cite web |date=18 May 2012 |title=Granit Xhaka wechselt im Sommer vom FCB zu Borussia Mönchengladbach |trans-title=Granit Xhaka is moving from FCB to Borussia Mönchengladbach in the summer |url=http://www.fcb.ch/news/show/byItemID/de-de/10044/27987/26/7/7 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130101110223/http://www.fcb.ch/news/show/byItemID/de-de/10044/27987/26/7/7 |archive-date=1 January 2013 |access-date=18 May 2012 |publisher=FC Basel 1893 |language=de}}</ref>

Xhaka made his debut in a [[2012–13 DFB-Pokal|DFB-Pokal]] first round match against [[Alemannia Aachen]] on 18 August 2012. Three days later, he made his first appearance in European competition for Borussia in 1–3 home lost to [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]] in qualification for the [[2012–13 UEFA Champions League]]. On 25 August, he made his Bundesliga debut in the team's opening match of [[2012–13 Bundesliga|the season]], a 2–1 home win against [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|TSG Hoffenheim]]. He scored his first and only goal of the season in a 3–2 loss at [[1. FC Nürnberg]].<ref name=kicker>{{cite news |url=https://www.kicker.de/granit-xhaka/spieler/bundesliga/2024-25/bayer-04-leverkusen |title=Granit Xhaka |access-date=31 March 2016 |website=kicker}}</ref>

In his second season at the club, Xhaka started 29 times and made five substitute appearances as Gladbach finished in sixth place in the [[2014–15 Bundesliga]].<ref name=kicker/> In 2014–15, Xhaka started all 34 [[2014–15 Bundesliga]] matches for Borussia<ref name=kicker/> and was named in the league's team of the season.<ref>{{cite news |date=25 May 2015 |title=Infografik: Die Top-11 der Saison 2014/15 |trans-title=Infographic: The top 11 of the 2014/15 season |url=http://www.bundesliga.de/de/liga/news/infografik-die-top-11-der-saison.jsp |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150717111132/http://www.bundesliga.de/de/liga/news/infografik-die-top-11-der-saison.jsp |archive-date=17 July 2015 |access-date=31 March 2016 |publisher=Bundesliga}}</ref> Borussia finished in third place to qualify for the [[2015–16 UEFA Champions League]].{{citation needed|date=January 2023}}

On 23 September 2015, Xhaka captained Borussia and scored his first goal of the season, heading in from [[Raffael (footballer)|Raffael]]'s free kick in a 4–2 win over [[FC Augsburg]]. In the next match, against [[VfB Stuttgart]], Xhaka again captained the side and scored a goal in a 3–1 win. On 30 September, he made his first appearance for Borussia in the Champions League proper in a 1–2 [[2015–16 UEFA Champions League group stage|group stage]] loss at home to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].<ref name=kicker/> Xhaka received his fifth red card for the team in his 95th game on 20 December, for striking his opponent in the first half; he voluntarily gave €20,000 to charity as an apology.<ref>{{cite news |title=Granit Xhaka pays his dues after Gladbach star racks up red cards |url=http://www.espnfc.co.uk/blog/the-toe-poke/65/post/2767083/gladbach-xhaka-pays-after-red-cards |access-date=11 June 2016 |website=ESPN FC |date=22 December 2015}}</ref>

===Arsenal===
[[File:Granit Xhaka 2018.jpg|thumb|upright|Xhaka playing for [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in 2018]]

On 25 May 2016, [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] signed Xhaka from Borussia Mönchengladbach for a fee of around £35&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Telegrafi |first=From |title=Arsenal reveal the figures of the transfer and the staggering salary of Xhaka - Telegrafi |url=https://telegrafi.com/en/Arsenal-reveal-the-staggering-transfer-and-salary-figures-of-Xhaka/ |access-date=2026-02-12 |website=telegrafi.com |language=en}}</ref> Xhaka was signed after Arsenal allegedly backed out of a proposed transfer for [[N'Golo Kanté]] due to the agent fees involved, which totalled more than £10&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite news |last=McNicholas |first=James |date=2020-04-17 |title=Vardy, Mata, Tevez and more: The inside stories of Arsenal's failed signings |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/1751137/2020/04/17/vardy-mata-tevez-and-more-the-inside-stories-of-arsenals-failed-signings/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20210426081705/https://theathletic.com/1751137/2020/04/17/vardy-mata-tevez-and-more-the-inside-stories-of-arsenals-failed-signings/ |archive-date=26 April 2021 |access-date=2026-02-12 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Xhaka made his first appearance for Arsenal (as a half-time substitution) in a 2–1 win against the [[MLS All-Stars]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=MLS All-Stars 1–2 Arsenal – Report |url=https://www.arsenal.com/match/report/1617/post/first-team/mls-all-stars-1-2-arsenal-report |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |date=29 July 2016 |access-date=30 July 2016}}</ref>

Xhaka made his competitive debut for Arsenal in the club's opening match of the [[2016–17 Premier League]] season, a 4–3 defeat to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], replacing midfielder [[Mohamed Elneny]] in the 65th minute whilst also picking up a yellow card in the process.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Premier League: FT: Arsenal 3-4 Liverpool |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/football/36741050 |access-date=2026-02-12 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> His first goal for the club came on 17 September 2016, a 25-yard thunderbolt in a 4–1 [[Premier League]] victory against [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37326798 |title=Hull City 1–4 Arsenal |website=BBC Sport |date=17 September 2016 |access-date=17 September 2016}}</ref> Four days later, he would score again from distance, this time from 30 yards in a 4–0 [[2016–17 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] defeat of [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2016-09-20 |title=Granit Xhaka and Lucas Perez give Arsenal plenty to smile about in 4-0 win |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/fa-league-cups/nottingham-forest-vs-arsenal-match-report-granit-xhaka-goal-lucas-perez-arsene-wenger-result-efl-cup-a7319556.html |access-date=2026-02-12 |website=The Independent |language=en}}</ref> Xhaka's first Arsenal red card – and eighth for club and country since April 2014 – came in a 3–2 win over [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] on 15 October 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/37594169 |title=Arsenal 3–2 Swansea City |website=BBC Sport |access-date=24 September 2016}}</ref> On 22 January 2017, Xhaka was sent off for the second time in the season, by referee [[Jonathan Moss (referee)|Jon Moss]], in Arsenal's 2–1 home win against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Skelton |first1=Jack |title=Arsenal 2–1 Burnley |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/38626832 |access-date=22 January 2017 |website=BBC Sport |date=22 January 2017}}</ref> After his first goal for the club in September, he would not score in the Premier League again until doing so in May, scoring the first goal of a 2–0 victory over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], ending United's run of 25 consecutive games unbeaten.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39760508 |title=Arsenal 2–0 Manchester United |website=BBC Sport |date=7 May 2017 |access-date=7 May 2017}}</ref>

Xhaka went on to feature throughout Arsenal's triumphant [[2016-17 FA Cup|FA Cup campaign]]. As so he started in the [[2017 FA Cup Final|Cup final]] against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] which the Gunners won 2–1.<ref name=FACup>{{cite web |url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=WXeS3rsW1Z8 | archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211118/WXeS3rsW1Z8| archive-date=18 November 2021 | url-status=live |title=Arsenal 2–1 Chelsea – Emirates FA Cup Final 2016/17 | date=28 May 2017|via=YouTube |publisher=FATV}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Xhaka also played in the [[2017 FA Community Shield|2017 Community Shield]] that Arsenal won on penalties over Chelsea.<ref name=CS>{{cite web |url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=sVwr6MxovYQ | archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211118/sVwr6MxovYQ| archive-date=18 November 2021 | url-status=live |title=Arsenal 1–1 Chelsea (4–1 Pens) – FA Community Shield | date=7 August 2017|via=YouTube |publisher=FATV}}{{cbignore}}</ref> His first goal of the 2017–18 season came in a 3–3 draw with Liverpool, Xhaka scored a 25-yard thunderbolt to take Arsenal from 2–1 to 2–2.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/42362392 |title=Arsenal 3–3 Liverpool |website=BBC Sport |date=22 December 2017 |access-date=9 January 2018}}</ref>

On 15 September 2018, Xhaka scored the first goal, from a direct free kick, in a 2–1 victory against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/sep/15/newcastle-arsenal-premier-league-report |title=Arsenal's Mesut Özil leaves Ciaran Clark and Newcastle too much to do |last=Taylor |first=Louise |date=15 September 2018 |newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=29 October 2018}}</ref> On 28 October 2018, he scored again from a free kick against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Fifield |first=Dominic |date=2018-10-28 |title=Crystal Palace's Luka Milivojevic holds his nerve to end Arsenal's winning run |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/oct/28/crystal-palace-arsenal-premier-league-match-report |access-date=2026-02-12 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 27 September 2019, Arsenal manager [[Unai Emery]] confirmed that Xhaka will be the new captain for the Gunners, replacing [[Laurent Koscielny]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49850242 |title=Granit Xhaka: Arsenal manager Unai Emery names midfielder as new captain |website=BBC Sport |date=27 September 2019 |access-date=27 September 2019}}</ref>

In the match against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] at the [[Emirates Stadium]] on 27 October 2019, Xhaka was at the center of criticism after being substituted off in the 61st minute.<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2019/10/28/granit-xhaka-arsenal-reaction-fans-video |title=Watch: Xhaka Mouths Off at Arsenal Fans as He's Subbed Off |agency=Associated Press |magazine=Sports Illustrated|date=27 October 2019 |access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref> The incident began when a portion of Arsenal fans started to cheer when his name was called to be replaced. He was booed as he walked off the pitch, and responded by making several sarcastic gestures and angrily saying "fuck off" twice to the fans who jeered his name. He also removed his jersey before walking straight down the tunnel.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2019-10-28 |title=WATCH: Arsenal captain Granit Xhaka tells fans to f*** off after being substituted against Crystal Palace |url=https://www.timesnownews.com/sports/football/article/watch-arsenal-captain-granit-xhaka-tells-fans-to-f-off-after-being-substituted-against-crystal-palace/508684 |access-date=2026-02-12 |website=www.timesnownews.com |language=en}}</ref> Xhaka's actions were met with significant criticism after the match, and manager [[Unai Emery]] described Xhaka's conduct as "wrong".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50202543 |title=Granit Xhaka: Arsenal captain 'wrong' to react to booing fans – Unai Emery |date=27 October 2019 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2019-10-28 |title='He was wrong': Unai Emery on Xhaka's angry reaction to fans' boos – video |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/video/2019/oct/28/he-was-wrong-unai-emery-granit-xhaka-reaction-fans-boos-video |access-date=2026-02-12 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Emery also suggested that Xhaka should apologise.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50225445 |title=Granit Xhaka: Arsenal captain should apologise for reaction, says Unai Emery |date=29 October 2019 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 30 October 2019 the club announced that Xhaka would be offered counselling.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50229350 |title=Granit Xhaka: Arsenal to offer counselling to midfielder after fans' argument |date=29 October 2019 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Arsenal later tweeted an explanation from Xhaka about the incident.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/arsenal/status/1189985747580936192 |title=The following is a message from Granit Xhaka...pic.twitter.com/YG5lBKmQvi |date=31 October 2019}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=December 2019}} On 5 November 2019, just a month and a week after his announcement as captain, Xhaka was stripped of the captain's armband. [[Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang]] took over as the captain after previously serving as vice captain.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/pierre-emerick-aubameyang-named-arsenal-20819249 |title=Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang appointed Arsenal captain after Granit Xhaka is axed |last=Maltby |first=Matt |date=5 November 2019 |newspaper=Daily Mirror|access-date=5 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50309446 |title=Granit Xhaka: Arsenal midfielder stripped of captaincy – Unai Emery |date=5 November 2019 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

After this incident, Xhaka began a hiatus from the first team squad and it was deemed highly likely that Xhaka would leave Arsenal in the upcoming January transfer window.<ref name="bt.com">{{Cite web |title=Xhaka reveals how Arteta paved his road to Arsenal redemption |url=https://www.bt.com/sport/football/fa-cup/granit-xhaka-road-to-redemption-arsenal-v-chelsea-fa-cup-final-preview |access-date=2026-02-12 |website=BT}}</ref> However, under the tenure of new manager [[Mikel Arteta]], Xhaka was reintroduced into the team as a key player and saw a sharp uptake in his form for the club and slowly began to win over the fans with whom he had previously had an oft fractious relationship.<ref name="bt.com"/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2020/07/31/arsenals-granit-xhaka-fought-back-depths-become-pillar-mikel/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220112/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2020/07/31/arsenals-granit-xhaka-fought-back-depths-become-pillar-mikel/ |archive-date=12 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |title=How Arsenal's Granit Xhaka fought back from the depths to become a pillar of Mikel Arteta revolution |first=Sam |last=Dean |date=31 July 2020 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Xhaka credited Arteta for this resurgence, claiming 'He [Arteta] turned me around and gave me a second chance and he showed me he trusted me and I tried to give him everything back.'<ref name="bt.com"/> On 1 August 2020, Xhaka was selected to start in the [[2020 FA Cup Final|FA Cup Final]] against Chelsea, and went on to win his second winners' medal as Arsenal won their 14th FA Cup.<ref name="bbc">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53546100 |title=Arsenal 2–1 Chelsea |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=1 August 2020 |access-date=2 August 2020}}</ref>

On 28 August 2020, Xhaka was in the starting 11 in the [[2020 FA Community Shield]], which Arsenal clinched a 5–4 victory over [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the penalty shootout after the match was 1–1 after 90 minutes.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Arsenal 1-1 Liverpool (5-4 on pens): Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang secures Community Shield shootout win |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12059158/arsenal-1-1-liverpool-5-4-on-pens-pierre-emerick-aubameyang-secures-community-shield-shootout-win |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20251119222526/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12059158/arsenal-1-1-liverpool-5-4-on-pens-pierre-emerick-aubameyang-secures-community-shield-shootout-win |archive-date=2025-11-19 |access-date=2026-02-12 |work=Sky Sports |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 13 December 2020, Arsenal hosted [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] in a Premier League fixture. Xhaka was [[Penalty card#Red card|sent off]] at the 56th minute, after clashing with [[Dwight McNeil]] and later grabbing [[Ashley Westwood (footballer, born 1990)|Ashley Westwood]] by the neck.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ames |first=Nick |date=2020-12-13 |title=Mikel Arteta says Xhaka red card 'worse' than Pépé's as Arsenal crisis deepens |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/dec/13/mikel-arteta-granit-xhaka-arsenal-burnley |access-date=2026-02-12 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The match eventually ended with Burnley winning 1–0 after teammate Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang scored an [[Own goal#Association football|own goal]] at the 73rd minute. On 26 December 2020, he scored his first Premier League goal of the [[2020–21 Premier League|2020–21 season]] from a free kick in a 3–1 home win against Chelsea.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2020-12-27 |title=Arsenal lifts gloom with 3-1 win against Chelsea in EPL |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/football/arsenal-lifts-gloom-with-3-1-win-against-chelsea-in-epl/story-bdcZDIuKXwAWZ6Uf3DFRLK.html |access-date=2026-02-12 |website=Hindustan Times |language=en}}</ref>

On 13 January 2022, Xhaka received a red card in an [[EFL Cup]] [[2021–22 EFL Cup#Semi-finals|semi-final]] first-leg tie against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref name="XhakaRedLIV">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/59889970|title=Liverpool 0–0 Arsenal: Hosts frustrated by 10-man Gunners in their Carabao Cup semi-final first leg|first=Harry|last=Poole|date=13 January 2022|accessdate=23 January 2022|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> It was his fifth overall red card in his Arsenal career.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Granit Xhaka exclusive interview: Arsenal midfielder insists he won't change despite red cards |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11670/12521125/granit-xhaka-exclusive-interview-arsenal-midfielder-insists-he-wont-change-despite-red-cards |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250206171502/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11670/12521125/granit-xhaka-exclusive-interview-arsenal-midfielder-insists-he-wont-change-despite-red-cards |archive-date=2025-02-06 |access-date=2026-02-12 |work=Sky Sports |language=en-GB}}</ref> The match eventually ended goalless.<ref name="XhakaRedLIV"/> Xhaka scored his first goal of the [[2021–22 Premier League|2021–22 season]] with a long-range strike from 25 yards out, that helped seal a 3–1 victory over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] at the [[Emirates Stadium]].<ref>{{Cite web |title='I couldn't write that story!' – Arteta thrilled with Xhaka thunderbolt as Arsenal beat Man Utd |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/i-couldn-t-write-that-story-arteta-thrilled-with-xhaka/bltc43fa5ab9bf7d0f0 |access-date=18 June 2022 |website=Goal}}</ref> His stunning strike was eventually named winner of the club's annual Goal of the Season.<ref>{{Cite web |title=🏆 2021/22 Goal of the Season: The winner is… |url=https://www.arsenal.com/premier-league-goal-of-the-season-vote-winner-granit-xhaka-manchester-united |access-date=18 June 2022 |publisher=Arsenal F.C.}}</ref> Xhaka scored his first goal of the [[2022–23 Arsenal F.C. season|2022–23 season]], with a third goal from close range against [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] in a 4–2 victory during their first home game of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Xhaka enjoying freedom to go forward |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/xhaka-enjoying-freedom-go-forward |access-date=17 August 2022 |publisher=Arsenal F.C.}}</ref>

===Bayer Leverkusen===
On 6 July 2023, Xhaka signed for Bundesliga club [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]] on a five-year contract for a fee of €25&nbsp;million (£21.4&nbsp;million).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66120275 |title=Granit Xhaka: Bayer Leverkusen sign Swiss midfielder from Arsenal for £21.4m. |website=BBC Sport |date=6 July 2023 |access-date=1 October 2023}}</ref> On 12 August, he made his debut in a [[2023–24 DFB-Pokal]] match, playing the full 90 minutes in an 8–0 win against [[FC Teutonia Ottensen|Teutonia Ottensen]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/dfb-pokal-der-maenner/spieltag/?spieledb_path=%2Fdatencenter%2Fdfb-pokal%2F2023-2024%2F1-runde%2Fteutonia-05-ottensen-bayer-04-leverkusen-2352632 |title=Teutonia 05 Ottensen 0–8 Bayer 04 Leverkusen |publisher=German Football Association |language=de |date=12 August 2023 }}</ref> On 23 February 2024, he scored his first goal for Leverkusen in a 2–1 victory against [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68385261 |title=Bayer Leverkusen 2–1 Mainz |publisher=BBC Sport |date=23 February 2024 |access-date=23 February 2024}}</ref>

On 14 April, Xhaka scored in Leverkusen's 5–0 win over [[Werder Bremen]] to clinch the club's first [[List of German football champions|German championship]].<ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |title=Bayer Leverkusen win first Bundesliga title, ending Bayern Munich's reign |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/sports/2024/4/14/bayer-leverkusen-win-first-bundesliga-title-ending-bayern-munichs-reign |access-date=2026-02-12 |website=Al Jazeera |language=en}}</ref> On 25 May, he scored the only goal against [[1. FC Kaiserslautern|Kaiserslautern]] in the [[2024 DFB-Pokal final|DFB-Pokal final]], which granted his club their second ever DFB-Pokal trophy, and secured their [[2023–24 Bayer 04 Leverkusen season|invincible double season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cerr9ymgp40t|title=Kaiserslautern 0–1 Bayer Leverkusen |date=25 May 2024|access-date=25 May 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

Xhaka scored the opening goal of the [[2024–25 Bundesliga]] season from long-distance against Borussia Mönchengladbach on 23 August 2024 as Leverkusen won 3–2; Xhaka did not celebrate out of respect for Gladbach.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-08-23 |title=Xhaka explains lack of goal-celebration: "Wanted to show Gladbach and its fans full respect." |url=https://bulinews.com/xhaka-explains-lack-goal-celebration-wanted-show-gladbach-and-its-fans-full-respect |access-date=2024-08-28 |website=Bundesliga News in English |language=en}}</ref>

===Sunderland===
On 30 July 2025, Xhaka returned to England, signing for newly promoted Premier League side [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] on a three-year contract for a reported initial fee of £13 million, with an additional £4 million in add-ons.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.safc.com/news/2025/july/30/safc-sign-granit-xhaka--/ |title=SAFC sign Granit Xhaka! |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |date=30 July 2025 |access-date=30 July 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kearns |first=Sean |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cx29nyd9d9wo |title=Sunderland sign Bayer Leverkusen midfielder Xhaka |website=BBC Sport |date=30 July 2025 |access-date=30 July 2025}}</ref> Afterwards, he was named as Sunderland captain by head coach [[Régis Le Bris]] ahead of the [[2025–26 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2025–26 season]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cd9jk02n3l0o |title='I'm here to win' – Xhaka named Sunderland captain |publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 August 2025 }}</ref> Later that year, on 3 November, he scored his first goal in a 1–1 draw with [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Starforth |first=Miles |date=2025-11-03 |title=Granit Xhaka pegs back Everton to deny Moyes winning return to Sunderland |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/nov/03/sunderland-everton-premier-league-match-report |access-date=2026-02-12 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

==International career==
===2008–2011: Youth levels and senior debut===
Xhaka has played for Swiss youth squad at the U-17 level. He participated in the [[FIFA U-17 World Cup|Under-17 World Cup]] in [[2009 FIFA U-17 World Cup|2009 in Nigeria]]. The Swiss team won the World Cup.<ref name= "Player statistics FIFA U17 World Cup">{{cite web |title=Player statistics FIFA U17 World Cup |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/statisticsandrecords/players/player=311558/index.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091028065252/http://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/statisticsandrecords/players/player=311558/index.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 October 2009 |publisher=FIFA |access-date=29 August 2010}}</ref>

He played his first game for the [[Switzerland national under-19 football team|Switzerland national under-19 team]] on 25 May 2010, as a substitute, as the team beat [[Austria national under-19 football team]] 3–2 in the [[Schwaz]], Austria. He scored his first goal for the U-19 on 7 September 2010 as the team won 3–0 against the [[Czech Republic national under-19 football team|Czech Republic]].{{citation needed|date=January 2023}}

Xhaka played his first game for the [[Switzerland national under-21 football team|under-21 side]] on 3 September 2010, as a substitute, as the team beat the [[Republic of Ireland under-21 national football team|Republic of Ireland]] 1–0 at the [[Cornaredo Stadium]] in [[Lugano]].<ref name="Match report Switzerland 1-0 Republic of Ireland">{{cite web |last= |year=2010 |title=Switzerland see off Ireland for play-off place |url=https://www.uefa.com/under21/match/2000066--switzerland-vs-republic-of-ireland/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100816061752/http://www.uefa.com/under21/matches/season%3D2011/round%3D2000006/match%3D2000066/index.html |archive-date=16 August 2010 |access-date=3 September 2010 |publisher=UEFA}}</ref> This was the last game in the [[2011 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification Group 2|qualification Group 2]] to the [[2011 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]]. Xhaka was member of the Swiss U-21 squad that competed in the final tournament, hosted by Denmark, between 11 and 25 June 2011. The Swiss team reached the final without conceding a goal, but lost to [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain]] 2–0.{{citation needed|date=January 2023}}

===2011–present: Senior tournaments and captaincy===
[[File:Granit Xhaka - Switzerland vs. Argentina, 29th February 2012.jpg|thumb|upright|Xhaka playing for [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] in 2012]]

Before making his international debut for [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]], Xhaka was still undecided whether to play for his birth country or [[Albania national football team|Albania]], and he complained to the Albanian sports media that the [[Albanian Football Federation]] was ignoring him whilst the Swiss Football Association was showing much more interest.<ref name=Albaniasoccer1>{{cite news |last=Begu |first=Yll |title=Në fokus / Granit Xhaka: Dua të luaj për Shqipërinë, por mungon interesimi i FSHF-së! |url=http://www.albaniasoccer.com/lajme/shqiperi/kombetarja/4627-ne-fokus--granit-xhaka-dua-te-luaj-per-shqiperine-por-mungon-interesimi-i-fshf-se.html |date=13 April 2011 |quote="Mesfushori i Bazelit, Granit Xhaka, së bashku me vëllanë e tij, Taulantin, kanë dëshirë për t'u bërë pjesë e kombëtares shqiptare, mirëpo deri më tash nuk kanë parë kurrfarë interesimi nga Federata Shqiptare e Futbollit që t'i afrojë ata në kombëtaren kuqezi.", further in the article Xhaka says: "“Në javët e fundit është bërë një presion i madh drejt nesh nga mediet lokale për të zgjedhur kombëtaren e Zvicrës dhe e kam të vështirë ta kuptoj përse askush nga FSHF-ja nuk ka reaguar për të shprehur interesim që ne të vishemi kuqezi”, ka theksuar Granit Xhaka.}}</ref>

Xhaka debuted for Switzerland at [[Wembley Stadium]] against [[England national football team|England]] in a 2–2 [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying]] draw on 4 June 2011.<ref name="Fulldebut">{{cite web |url=http://football.uk.reuters.com/leagues/uk/news/2011/06/04/LDE7530D0.php | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120311104620/http://football.uk.reuters.com/leagues/uk/news/2011/06/04/LDE7530D0.php | url-status = dead | archive-date = 11 March 2012 |title=Below-par England salvage draw with Switzerland |work=Reuters |date=4 June 2011 |access-date=5 June 2011 |last=Collett |first=Mike}}</ref> On 15 November 2011, during his sixth international appearance, he scored his first international goal in the 1–0 away win against [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]] at the [[Stade Josy Barthel]].<ref name="sfv 3">{{cite web |year=2011 |title=Matchtelegram Luxembourg-Schweiz |trans-title=Match report Luxembourg vs. Switzerland |url=http://www.football.ch/nm/de/A_Team-telegramm.aspx?tg=1921952 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130115214415/http://www.football.ch/nm/de/A_Team-telegramm.aspx?tg=1921952 |archive-date=15 January 2013 |access-date=15 November 2011 |publisher=Swiss Football Association |language=de}}</ref>

Switzerland also tried to select Xhaka to participate in the [[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2012 Olympic Football tournament]], but he opted to stay at his new club for pre-season training.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/oly-socc-swiss-squad-idUSB29215720120709 |title=Olympics-Shaqiri, Xhaka excluded from Swiss soccer squad |work=Reuters |date=9 July 2012 |access-date=27 July 2012}}</ref> He participated in all ten of Switzerland's [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2014 FIFA World Cup qualification campaign]] matches, scoring both goals in a 2–0 defeat of [[Slovenia national football team|Slovenia]].<ref name=fifa>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/players/player=311558/played-matches.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140619085859/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/players/player=311558/played-matches.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 June 2014 |title=Granit XHAKA |access-date=21 June 2014 |publisher=FIFA}}</ref> On 2 June 2014, Xhaka was named in Switzerland's [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]] squad by national coach [[Ottmar Hitzfeld]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/switzerland/10810381/Switzerland-World-Cup-2014-squad.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220112/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/switzerland/10810381/Switzerland-World-Cup-2014-squad.html |archive-date=12 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |title=Switzerland World Cup 2014 squad |date=2 June 2014 |access-date=16 June 2014 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}{{cbignore}}</ref> In the team's second match, Xhaka scored in a 5–2 loss to [[France national football team|France]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/25285207 |title=Switzerland 2–5 France |date=20 June 2014 |access-date=21 June 2014 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

Xhaka was selected for [[UEFA Euro 2016]], where Switzerland's campaign opened against Albania in [[Lens, Pas-de-Calais|Lens]]. Xhaka, whose team won 1–0, was playing against his brother [[Taulant Xhaka|Taulant]]. He was voted the [[Player of the match|man of the match]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Atkin |first1=John |title=Switzerland hold on against ten-man Albania |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/history/news/0253-0d816e2f318a-e54e130e4b00-1000--switzerland-hold-on-against-ten-man-albania-in-euro-2016-gr/ |access-date=25 June 2016 |publisher=UEFA |date=11 June 2016}}</ref> Xhaka played every minute of Switzerland's campaign, which ended in the round of 16 with a loss to [[Poland national football team|Poland]] at the [[Stade Geoffroy-Guichard]]; after a 1–1 draw he was the only player to not score in the [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]], shooting wide.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Brassell |first=Andy |date=2016-06-25 |title=Poland hold nerve after Switzerland's Granit Xhaka blazes penalty wide |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/jun/25/switzerland-poland-euro-2016-match-report |access-date=2026-02-12 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

Ahead of the [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2018 World Cup qualifiers]], there was speculation that Xhaka could switch his allegiance to represent [[Kosovo national football team|Kosovo]], which had been accepted as a full member of [[FIFA]] and were allowed to play competitive matches for the first time. Xhaka, however, published an open letter stating that his participation in Euro 2016 had disqualified him from changing his allegiance, and he was thus tied to Switzerland.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://talentet.eu/2016/08/30/leter-e-hapur-nga-granit-xhaka/ |title=Letër e hapur nga Granit XHAKA – TALENTËT |website=talentet.eu|access-date=6 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160905024345/http://talentet.eu/2016/08/30/leter-e-hapur-nga-granit-xhaka/|archive-date=5 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Xhaka was named in manager [[Vladimir Petković]]'s 23-man Swiss squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia.<ref>{{cite news |title=2018 World Cup: Switzerland name Granit Xhaka and Xherdan Shaqiri in squad |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44360966 |access-date=22 June 2018 |website=BBC Sport |date=4 June 2018}}</ref> On 22 June, he equalised with a long-range strike as the Swiss came from behind to defeat [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]] 2–1 in their second game. He and fellow goalscorer [[Xherdan Shaqiri]], who is also of Albanian descent, [[Goal celebration|celebrated their goals]] by making an [[Crossed hands|eagle gesture]] resembling the double headed eagle of the [[Flag of Albania|Albanian flag]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Lowe |first=Sid |date=2018-06-22 |title=Switzerland's Xherdan Shaqiri stuns Serbia with late breakaway |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/jun/22/serbia-switzerland-xherdan-shaqiri-world-cup-group-e-match-report |access-date=2026-02-12 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077 |quote=As he turned and screamed, he took his shirt off, flexed his muscles and performed a double-eagle celebration, a recreation of the Albanian flag. Alongside him, Granit Xhaka did the same – for the second time.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Lowe |first=Sid |date=2018-06-23 |title=Switzerland's Xhaka and Shaqiri charged by Fifa over Serbia goal celebrations |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/jun/23/xhaka-and-shaqiri-goal-celebrations-bring-balkan-politics-to-world-cup |access-date=2026-02-12 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2018-06-23 |title=The Swiss media weren't happy with Shaqiri and Xhaka's goal celebrations |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/world-cup-2018-switzerland-serbia-granit-xhaka-xherdan-shaqiri-goal-celebrations-why-controversial-kosovo-serbia-albania-eagle-flag-a8413426.html |access-date=2026-02-12 |website=The Independent |language=en}}</ref> FIFA fined each player 10,000 [[Swiss franc]]s "for unsporting behaviour contrary to the principles of fair-play".<ref>{{cite news |title=World Cup 2018: Switzerland trio avoid bans for 'eagle gesture' goal celebrations |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44606965 |access-date=25 June 2018 |website=BBC Sport |date=25 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=World Cup 2018: Granit Xhaka and Xherdan Shaqiri avoid bans after political goal celebrations |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/world-cup-2018-granit-xhaka-xherdan-shaqiri-goal-celebrations-albania-kosovo-serbia-fine-a8416466.html |access-date=25 June 2018 |website=BBC Sport |date=25 June 2018}}</ref>

Xhaka was appointed as a temporary captain by Vladimir Petković in the absence of [[Stephan Lichtsteiner]], which caused him to be criticised by former Swiss international [[Stéphane Henchoz]], who claimed that Xhaka could not properly represent Switzerland due to his Albanian heritage, instead suggesting that Lichtsteiner, [[Yann Sommer]], or [[Fabian Schär]] serve as captain.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2018-09-05 |title=Granit Xhaka would be a bad choice to captain Switzerland, says Stephane Henchoz |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/granit-xhaka-should-not-captain-switzerland-does-not-represent-country-stephane-henchoz-stephan-lichtsteiner-arsenal-video-a8524616.html |access-date=2026-02-12 |website=The Independent |language=en}}</ref> In September 2019, Xhaka offered his captaincy to Xherdan Shaqiri in an effort to get him to return to the national side.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/6449232-arsenal-s-granit-xhaka-willing-to-give-up-switzerland-captaincy-to-see-xherdan-shaqiri-return |title=Arsenal's Granit Xhaka Willing to Give Up Switzerland Captaincy to See Xherdan Shaqiri Return |date=6 September 2019 |website=90min.com|access-date=27 September 2019}}</ref>

In June 2021, Xhaka was selected for the Switzerland squad for [[UEFA Euro 2020]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=published |first=FourFourTwo Staff |date=2021-06-04 |title=Switzerland Euro 2020 squad profile: Best player, manager and past Euros record |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/switzerland-euro-2020-squad-the-complete-line-up-for-marchs-internationals |access-date=2026-02-12 |website=FourFourTwo |language=en}}</ref> He captained the team in their three group matches, as well as the [[UEFA Euro 2024 knockout stage#Round of 16|round of 16]] tie with France. In the match against France, he assisted [[Mario Gavranović]]'s 90th-minute equalising goal as Switzerland progressed to the quarter-final via a penalty shootout.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/commentary/_/gameId/560303|title= Switzerland beats France 5–4 on penalties at Euro 2020|website=ESPN|date=29 June 2021|access-date=16 June 2024}}</ref> However, a yellow card received 14 minutes earlier meant that Xhaka was suspended for the quarter-final, where the Swiss lost to [[Spain national football team|Spain]] in a penalty shootout.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51198650|title=Switzerland 1–1 Spain: Spain beat Switzerland on penalties to reach Euros semis|date=1 July 2021|website=BBC Sport|access-date=16 June 2024}}</ref>

In November 2022, Xhaka was selected for the 26-man Switzerland squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in Qatar.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-12-06 |title=Switzerland World Cup squad 2022: Final list of 26 players for national team in Qatar {{!}} Sporting News |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/soccer/news/switzerland-world-cup-squad-2022-players-national-team-roster-26/qiqh3gw0mq8qwfyr7z2pag5r |access-date=2026-02-12 |website=www.sportingnews.com |language=en-us}}</ref> He played every minute of Switzerland's four matches of the tournament as they reached the [[2022 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Round of 16|round of 16]], where they were beaten 6–1 by [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51198650|title=Portugal 6–1 Switzerland: Ronaldo replacement Ramos scores hat-trick as Portugal advance|date=5 December 2022|website=BBC Sport|access-date=16 June 2024}}</ref>

On 15 October 2023, in a 3–3 draw with [[Belarus national football team|Belarus]] during [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying]], Xhaka equalled [[Heinz Hermann]]'s record of 118 appearances for the Swiss national team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bayer04.de/en-us/news/bayer04/international-update-xhaka-equals-swiss-record-werkself-trio-in-action-with-germany| title= INTERNATIONAL UPDATE: XHAKA EQUALS SWISS RECORD – WERKSELF TRIO IN ACTION WITH GERMANY|date=18 October 2023|access-date=16 June 2024|website=Bayer 04 Leverkusen}}</ref> A month later, he captained the ''Nati'' in a 1–1 draw in [[Israel national football team|Israel]] to break the record with his 119th appearance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/article/granit-xhaka-switzerland-record-appearance-f84e851e2f118d71943c90dd9a662c47|title=Granit Xhaka sets Switzerland record with 119th national team game in Euro 2024 qualifier |date=16 November 2023|access-date=16 June 2024|website=Bayer 04 Leverkusen}}</ref>

In June 2024, Xhaka was named in Switzerland's squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]]. He captained the team to 3–1 over [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] in their opening [[UEFA Euro 2024 Group A|Group A]] match and was named [[Man of the match]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cy99107knekt|title=Hungary 1–3 Switzerland LIVE: UEFA Euro 2024 – score, updates & reaction|website=BBC Sport|access-date=16 June 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Segar |first=David |date=2024-06-15 |title=Hungary 1-3 Switzerland Stats: Swiss Enjoy Strong Start at Euro 2024 |url=https://theanalyst.com/articles/hungary-vs-switzerland-stats-euro-2024-live |access-date=2026-02-12 |website=Opta Analyst |language=en}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Xhaka's elder brother, [[Taulant Xhaka]] was also a professional footballer who played for [[FC Basel|Basel]] and previously represented the [[Albania national football team|Albania national team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panorama.com.al/2011/11/16/xhaka-zgjodha-pa-hezitim-zvicren-shqiptaret-me-thone-tradhtar/|title=Xhaka: Zgjodha pa hezitim Zvicrën, shqiptarët më thonë tradhtar!|quote=Granit, familja juaj vjen nga Kosova, po ju ku keni lindur? Në Zvicër, në Bazel kam lindur. Ashtu si Taulanti, vëllai im. Disa burime informacioni, duke përfshirë këtu edhe "Ëikipedia", kanë njoftuar se kam lindur në Kosovë, por kjo nuk është e vërtetë|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140514225243/http://www.panorama.com.al/2011/11/16/xhaka-zgjodha-pa-hezitim-zvicren-shqiptaret-me-thone-tradhtar/|archive-date=14 May 2014}}</ref> In July 2017, Xhaka married his long-term partner, Leonita Lekaj.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/granit-xhaka-married-leonita-lekaj-10753757 |title=Arsenal star Granit Xhaka marries long-term partner Leonita Lekaj as team-mates return for pre-season training |first=Marc |last=Isaacs |date=7 July 2017 |access-date=11 January 2018 |newspaper=Daily Mirror}}</ref> They have three daughters, born in 2019,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B3WxP1kAm_S/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/iarchive/s/instagram/B3WxP1kAm_S |archive-date=26 December 2021 |url-access=registration |title=Leonita Xhaka on Instagram |date=8 October 2019 |via=Instagram}}{{cbignore}}</ref> 2021 and 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Critchlow |first=Dan |date=25 April 2021 |title=Granit Xhaka announces birth of 2nd child |url=https://dailycannon.com/2021/04/granit-xhaka-baby/ |access-date=17 August 2022 |language=en-US}}</ref>

